m]] in Game 7 of the [[2004 American League Championship Series]],{{efn|Game 7 of the 2004 American League Championship Series was played on October 20 at Yankee Stadium in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2004/B10200NYA2004.htm |title=Boston Red Sox 10, New York Yankees 3 |website=[[Retrosheet]] |date=October 20, 2004 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The game started at approximately 8:00 p.m. and ended at approximately midnight.<ref name=Commission/> Police crowd-control activities near Fenway Park in Boston took place in the early hours of October 21.<ref name=Commission/>}} the [[Boston Police Department]] took action around [[Fenway Park]] to control a crowd that had gathered, some of whom were throwing bottles at the police.<ref name=Commission/> Approximately 90 minutes after the game ended, officer Rochefort Milien shot Snelgrove with an [[FN 303]] blunt [[Physical trauma|trauma]] / [[pepper spray]] projectile. Snelgrove, who was not acting in an unruly manner, was not Milien's intended target; he had fired at a different person in the crowd.<ref name=Commission/> The crowd-control projectile hit Snelgrove in the eye, causing her to bleed excessively. Ambulances were blocked by the excessive crowds, which still refused to clear the area, preventing prompt medical attention from arriving from the dense medical area only a half-mile (0.8 km) away.<ref name=Commission>{{cite document |url=http://www.cityofboston.gov/police/pdfs/report.pdf |title=Commission Investigating the Death of Victoria Snelgrove |page=14 |date=May 25, 2005 |accessdate=April 25, 2009 |website=cityofboston.gov |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610210149/www.cityofboston.gov/police/pdfs/report.pdf |archivedate=June 10, 2011 |via=[[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref>\n\nSnelgrove died at 12:50&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern daylight time|EDT]] at [[Brigham and Women's Hospital]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]],<ref name=Commission/> about 12 hours after being shot. According to the [[autopsy]], the pellet opened a three-quarter-inch (1.9 cm) hole in the bone behind the eye, broke into nine pieces, and damaged the right side of her brain.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46757370/in-snelgrove-files-officers-recount/ |title=In Snelgrove files, officers recount night of chaos |first1=Donovan |last1=Slack |first2=Suzanne |last2=Smalley |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |page=1 |date=September 21, 2005 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBoston's [[Police commissioner#United States|Police Commissioner]], [[Kathleen O'Toole]], placed Milien on paid leave.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/print/2004/nov/13/nation/na-fan13|title=Red Sox Fan Killed by Stray Shot, Police Say|date=November 13, 2004|agency=[[Associated Press|AP]]|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> O'Toole later attended the hour-long funeral on October 26, 2004, at St. John's [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] church in [[East Bridgewater, Massachusetts]], along with [[Mayor of Boston]] [[Thomas Menino]] and [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Mitt Romney]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46759343/funeral-held-for-fan-killed-in/ |title=Funeral held for fan killed in celebrations |newspaper=[[Pensacola News Journal]] |date=October 27, 2004 |first=Denise |last=Lavoie |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46759115/a-precious-life-lost-senselessly-is/ |title=A precious life, lost senselessly, is mourned |first=Brian |last=MacQuarrie |first2=Julie |last2=Polovina |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=October 27, 2004 |page=B4 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation and aftermath==\nCommissioner O'Toole accepted the police department's responsibility, while condemning the \"punks\" who turned the event into a near-[[riot]] as the real cause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/articles/2004/10/22/postgame_police_projectile_kills_an_emerson_student/|title=O'Toole accepts responsibility but condemns acts of 'punks'|work=Boston Globe|first=Thomas|last=Farragher|date=October 22, 2004|accessdate=February 20, 2011}}</ref> The investigation into Snelgrove's death was led by [[Donald K. Stern]], a former [[United States Attorney]] best known for prosecuting [[organized crime|mob]] figures, including fugitive [[Winter Hill Gang]] leader [[Whitey Bulger|James \"Whitey\" Bulger]].  Through the investigation, Officer Milien was identified as the person who fired the shot that killed Snelgrove.<ref name=Commission/> The report from the investigation outlined 12 recommendations for the Boston Police Department, including a review of use-of-force policies and improved training for less-lethal weapons.<ref name=Commission/> On May 2, 2005, the city of Boston announced a $5.1 million [[wrongful death claim|wrongful death]] settlement for her family's lawsuit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://dailycollegian.com/2005/05/51-million-settlement-reached-for-wrongful-death-in-04-red-sox-riots/ |title=$5.1 million settlement reached for wrongful death in \u201904 Red Sox riots |first=Michael |last=Kunzelman |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=Massachusetts Daily Collegian |date=May 3, 2005 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2005, the [[district attorney]] for [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], [[Daniel F. Conley]], announced that he would not prosecute any of the officers involved.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mass.gov/da/suffolk/docs/091205.html |title=Investigative Findings in the Oct. 21, 2004 Fatal Police Shooting of Victoria Snelgrove |publisher=Suffolk County District Attorney's Office |website=mass.gov |accessdate=October 26, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051226021746/www.mass.gov/da/suffolk/docs/091205.html |archivedate=December 26, 2005 |via=[[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref> Four days later, Commissioner O'Toole demoted the police superintendent who was in charge the night of the shooting to captain and suspended two officers, including Milien, for 45 days without pay.<ref name=Suspended>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46771626/2-suspended-for-fenway-shootings/ |title=2 suspended for Fenway shootings |first=Suzanne |last=Smalley |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |page=1 |date=September 17, 2005 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> The deputy superintendent outside Fenway Park at the time of the incident was also criticized for poor decisions that led to Snelgrove's death, but had already retired.<ref name=Suspended/> {{asof|2019|10}}, Officer Milien was still on the Boston police force.<ref>{{cite document |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5086f19ce4b0ad16ff15598d/t/5db0b206093adc41ef82603a/1571860998768/district_journal_arrests_public+%2814%29.pdf |title=District Journal for Oct 22, 2019 - Oct 23, 2019, District: ALL |publisher=Boston Police Department |via=squarespace.com |date=October 2019 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe weapon that killed Snelgrove was manufactured by Fabrique Nationale de Herstal ([[FN Herstal]]). Because of the incident, several police forces, such as the [[Seattle Police Department]], discontinued use of this weapon.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/newsArticle.jhtml?type=domesticNews&storyID=6649956 |title=Seattle Suspends Pepper Gun Used in Boston Death |access-date=November 28, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041112032629/http://www.reuters.com/newsArticle.jhtml?type=domesticNews&storyID=6649956 |archive-date=November 12, 2004 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In July 2006, a $10 million lawsuit between FN Herstal and the Snelgrove family was settled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snelgrove family settles lawsuit |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2006/07/14/snelgrove_family_settles_lawsuit/ |date=2006-07-14 |author=Murphy, Shelley |accessdate=2012-02-06 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Boston police never used their FN 303s again, and destroyed them in 2007, stating that they were more powerful and lethal than had been anticipated.<ref>{{cite news|title=BPD: Pellet guns to be destroyed |url=http://media.www.berkeleybeacon.com/media/storage/paper169/news/2007/03/01/News/Bpd-Pellet.Guns.To.Be.Destroyed-2755628.shtml/ |date=2007-03-01 |author=Shea, Paddy |accessdate=2009-06-05 |work=[[Berkeley Beacon]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822051610/http://media.www.berkeleybeacon.com/media/storage/paper169/news/2007/03/01/News/Bpd-Pellet.Guns.To.Be.Destroyed-2755628.shtml |archivedate=August 22, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Memorials==\n[[Stephen King]] and [[Stewart O'Nan]] dedicated their book, ''Faithful: Two Diehard Boston Red Sox Fans Chronicle The Historic 2004 Season'', to Snelgrove; the dedication reads simply: \"For Victoria Snelgrove, Red Sox fan.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.amazon.com/Faithful-Diehard-Boston-Chronicle-Historic/dp/0743267524/ |title=Faithful: Two Diehard Boston Red Sox Fans Chronicle The Historic 2004 Season |page=ix |isbn=0743267524 |publisher=Scribner |first1=Stewart |last1=O'Nan |first2=Stephen |last2=King |date=2004 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Red Sox [[outfielder]] [[Trot Nixon]] stated that he would have traded Game 7 of the [[2004 American League Championship Series|2004 ALCS]] to have her back.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46762244/pesky-happy-to-be-back/ |title=Pesky Happy to be Back |date=October 23, 2004 |first=Bob |last=Hohler |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |page=E5 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nSnelgrove's parents established the Victoria Snelgrove Memorial Fund, \"a non-profit organization to carry forward her spirit and concern for others,\" which awards scholarships to students at [[East Bridgewater High School]] and Emerson College.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.victoriasnelgrove.com |title=Victoria Snelgrove Memorial Fund |website=victoriasnelgrove.com |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> In April 2018, a [[skatepark]] in East Bridgewater was opened and named after Snelgrove.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://whdh.com/news/skate-park-dedicated-to-woman-killed-after-2004-red-sox-playoff-win/ |title=Skate park dedicated to woman killed after 2004 Red Sox playoff win |website=whdh.com |date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.cnn.com/2004/US/10/22/fan.death/ \"Boston police accept 'full responsibility' in death of Red Sox fan\"], CNN.  October 22, 2004.\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/27/sports/baseball/27funeral.html \"Violence Denounced in Eulogy for College Student\"] ''The New York Times''. AP. October 27, 2004\n* [http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2004/11/13/video_clip_records_fatal_fenway_shooting?pg=full \"Video clip records fatal Fenway shooting\"], ''The Boston Globe''.  November 13, 2004.\n*{{cite news |url=http://bostondirtdogs.boston.com/Headline_Archives/2005/05/well_never_forg_1.html |title=Don't Ever Forget What Happened to Torie |website=Boston Dirt Dogs |via=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 2, 2005}}\n*[https://archive.today/20130812172902/http://jsons.collegepublisher.com/media/paper139/news/2005/06/03/Bostonregion/Stern.Commission.Report.Criticizes.Boston.Police.In.Snelgrove.Death-954791.shtml \"Stern Commission Report criticizes Boston Police in Snelgrove death\"] ''The Berkeley Beacon''. Michael Corcoran. June 3, 2005\n*[http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2005/09/21/in_snelgrove_files_officers_recount_night_of_chaos/?page=full%3Cbr%20/%3E \"In Snelgrove files, officers recount night of chaos\"] ''The Boston Globe'', September 21, 2005\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.victoriasnelgrove.com Victoria Snelgrove Memorial Fund]\n* {{findagrave|9718624|Victoria E. Snelgrove}}\n\n{{Boston Police Department}}\n{{Boston Red Sox}}\n\n{{D